The latitude of the place being described in the current record. (Latitude lines are the bands that run around the earth parallel to the equator, with values of 0° <= x <= 90, all except 0 [the equator] taking a designation of North or South.)

The longitude of the place being described in the current record. (Longitude lines are the bands that run around the earth via the North and South poles, with values of 0° <= x <= 180°, all except 0 [Greenwich Meridian] and 180 [International Date Line] taking a designation of East or West.)

The UTM of a site - an alternative method of pinpointing a location to Latitude and Longitude. Values are determined by UTM zones (which function much like time zones), and then subdivisions of a zone into grids that indicate metres. The point of origin in zones in the northern hemisphere is in the south-west corner - hence all northern hemisphere UTM valueshave East and North designations. In the southern hemisphere, the point of origin is in the north-west corner and values have a South designation. For example, a UTM value of north 4,276,750 and east 357,800 will be in the northern hemisphere (in a zone that is usually assumed to be known).

The broadest division in the simple hierarchy; a continent conventionally is a large, continuous, discrete mass of land, ideally separated by expanses of water. In TGN, the Simple Hierarchy (& hence the divisions/designations) is intended to work with inhabited places (political divisions), but not necessarily with physical features.
Distance above sea level measured in feet.
Distance above sea level measured in meters.

Facets constitute the major subdivisions of the Getty AAT/TGN hierarchical structure. A facet contains a homogeneous class of concepts, the members of which share characteristics that distinguish them from members of other classes. For AAT, this field records the legacy Facet & Hierarchy codes.

The 3rd broadest division in the simple hierarchy. In TGN, the Simple Hierarchy (& hence the divisions/designations) is intended to work with inhabited places (political divisions), but not necessarily with physical features.

The narrowest division in the simple hierarchy. In TGN, the Simple Hierarchy (& hence the divisions/designations) is intended to work with inhabited places (political divisions), but not necessarily with physical features.

Latitude (Lat.) is the angular distance north or south of the equator, measured along a meridian (expressed in degrees and minutes). While many records in TGN include coordinates, these coordinates are approximate and are intended for reference ("finding purposes") only.

Longitude (Long.) is the angular distance east or west of the Prime Meridian at Greenwich, England (expressed in degrees and minutes). While many records in TGN include coordinates, these coordinates are approximate and are intended for reference ("finding purposes") only.

The 2nd broadest division in the simple hierarchy; a nation is the primary political unit. Conventionally, it refers to a large group of people who share a common language, culture, ethnicity, descent, or history. In TGN, the Simple Hierarchy (& hence the divisions/designations) is intended to work with inhabited places (political divisions), but not necessarily with physical features.

Decimal Latitude (Lat.) is the angular distance north or south of the equator, measured along a meridian (expressed in decimal fractions of degrees). While many records in TGN include coordinates, these coordinates are approximate and are intended for reference ("finding purposes") only.

Decimal Longitude (Long.) is the angular distance east or west of the Prime Meridian at Greenwich, England (expressed in decimal fractions of degrees). While many records in TGN include coordinates, these coordinates are approximate and are intended for reference ("finding purposes") only.

The RHS of the year range that delimit the span of time referred to in the date period for the place type. End Dates are years in the proleptic Gregorian calendar. If the place type is still applicable to the current place, the End Date is 9999. The dates refer to usage of the name, not necessarily tied to the dates of existence the place.

The LHS of the year range that delimit the span of time referred to in the date period for the place type. Start Dates are years in the proleptic Gregorian calendar. Dates BCE are indexed with negative numbers. The dates refer to usage of the name, not necessarily tied to the dates of existence the place.
The place type in the TGN is a term that characterizes a significant aspect of the place, including its role, function, political anatomy, size, or physical characteristics.

The 4th broadest division in the simple hierarchy. In TGN, the Simple Hierarchy (& hence the divisions/designations) is intended to work with inhabited places (political divisions), but not necessarily with physical features.
